<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / Money Markets: UK rate cut hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHANIE FLANDERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE was strong speculation in sterling interest rate markets yesterday
that the UK authorities would cut base rates in the next few weeks, writes
Stephanie Flanders.
The speculation was partly fuelled by a belief that a cut in Germany's
discount rate this week would help the UK to ease monetary policy again.
A report from the Confederation of British Industry on Tuesday that UK
exports could have been hit by the higher sterling exchange rate in recent
months also added to speculation that the UK would want to try to bring down
the value of the pound.
'Most of the shift in expectations seems to have come directly from Tuesday
evening's news reports,' said one observer. 'Rates had got stuck at a level
which implied that cutting rates was a fairly free option, and now the
market has begun to concentrate harder on precisely when it will occur.'
Caught up most with the new mood was trading in sterling futures. The
September contract gained a full 18 basis points, closing at around 94.36,
while the December contract was similarly affected, ending 17 basis points
higher at 94.58.
However, some dealers felt that an early cut in base rates was hard to
envisage. 'If anything, the futures market has over-reacted,' said a London
analyst. 'Every piece of paper says that there will be a cut in rates around
budget time, not at the end of this week, but clearly a lot will depend on
events in Europe.'
At the short end, there was a lingering Pounds 2.25bn shortage, dispatched
by discount market operations throughout the day and a small amount of late
assistance from the Bank of England. Observers said the delay could be
traced to the 'wait and see' attitude of a number of players, pondering the
new thinking on UK interest rates. Overnight rates peaked at 7 3/4 per cent,
but later closed at around 6 per cent.
In Paris, developments in the French markets reflected the belief that a
German interest rate reduction at today's central bank council meeting,
combined with a significant domestic fiscal stimulus, might allow the French
franc to retain its parity for the rest of the summer.
Three-month French money market rates fell to around 8.25 per cent, down 100
basis points on the day. Trading in French franc futures was also affected,
with the September Pibor contract closing at 92.78, down two basis points
from the previous day, and the December contract ending 5 basis points lower
at 94.03.
</TEXT>
