<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / International Company News: Nomura bails out property
division
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GORDON CRAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NOMURA Securities, the world's largest stockbroker, yesterday joined the
list of Japan's financial institutions forced into a costly corporate
restructuring by the collapse of property prices.
It is bailing out a troubled property lending affiliate - Nomura Finance -
by merging it with another offshoot. The move will allow the write-off of
Y200bn (Dollars 1.87bn) in bad loans, a cost which the group is to absorb.
The demise of Nomura Finance is a further indication of the problems
besetting non-bank financial institutions in Japan. It follows a number of
similar moves by commercial banks to ease the burden of their non-bank
subsidiaries, and could form a precedentfor other brokerage houseswhich are
similarly afflicted.
The bail-out is the second blow in a week for Nomura - last Thursday, Mr
Joseph Perella quit Wasserstein Perella, the Wall Street investment bank he
co-founded and into which Nomura sank Dollars 100m for a 20 per cent stake.
Nomura Finance, created in 1989 at the height of the property boom, had
operating assets of Y1,462bn as of March, but non-performing and other
doubtful loans put yesterday at Y330bn. It is being subsumed by Ivy Real
Estate, a subsidiary of Nomura Land and Building, a property management
unit.
Of the bad loans, Y200bn will be written off, financed by Ivy's unrealised
profits on landholdings, a capital increase by Ivy, and a Y100bn injection
from Nomura Securities over 10 years, for which it will receive
mortgage-backed paper.
Companies in the Nomura group together own 68.5 per cent of Nomura Finance,
although the stockbroker holds only 5 per cent. The stake is thus not
consolidated in Nomura Securities' group accounts, and the company insisted
yesterday's move would have no direct impact on profits.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
