<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / Cigarette cloud over BAT's 35% increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE and RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Patrick Sheehy, chairman of BAT Industries, warned yesterday, that the
US cigarette price war 'is hurting us and its effects will continue to be
felt into 1994 and beyond'.
His comments came as the tobacco and financial services group reported a 35
per cent increase in first-half pre-tax profits from Pounds 672m to Pounds
906m.
During the six months, the impact of the US cigarette price battle was
largely confined to a Dollars 75m (Pounds 50.3m) fall in the trading profits
of Brown and Williamson, BAT's US subsidiary, due to stock reductions.
However, BAT is to cut the price of its premium brands in the US next month
to match the discounting of Marlboro by Philip Morris and of Winston by RJ
Reynolds.
Overall trading profits from the tobacco business rose from Pounds 518m to
Pounds 623m on turnover of Pounds 5.63bn, against Pounds 5.51bn. Excluding a
one-off gain of Pounds 135m from the recent cigarette brands swap with
American Brands, profits declined 6 per cent, reflecting depressed economic
conditions in a number of international markets.
The group was also hit by unexpected losses at Eagle Star, its general
insurance subsidiary, on mortgage indemnity policies - covering mortgage
lenders against losses on sales of repossessed property - underwritten
between 1988 and 1990.
These losses amounted to Pounds 57m, offsetting profits of Pounds 45m from
other areas of Eagle Star's general and life insurance business. 'The surge
in mortgage claims took us by surprise both in terms of number and cost,'
said Mr Martin Broughton, chief executive.
Other areas of Eagle Star's general business showed improvement as a result
of a fall in weather and recession-related claims and rises in premium
rates. The group's home and motor insurance lines both recorded underwriting
profits. The improvement was in spite of expected claims of Pounds 24m from
the Bishopsgate bomb in the City of London.
Allied Dunbar, the group's UK life insurance arm, and Farmers Group, its US
subsidiary, helped boost profits from financial services to more than Pounds
300m.
Earnings were helped by a low tax charge of 29.6 per cent, following high
take-up of the enhanced share alternative to the cash dividend.
Earnings per share grew 66 per cent from 11.8p to 19.6p; and the interim
dividend is raised 8 per cent to 7.9p
Lex, Page 16; Details, Page 18
