<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / This Is Your Life inspires Thames deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THAMES Television, the independent television production company that lost
its ITV franchise, has struck a deal with the BBC worth more than Pounds 20m
over three years.
At the heart of the deal is This Is Your Life, a programme that started life
at the BBC 38 years ago, moved to ITV and will now move back to the BBC in
autumn 1994. The programme's simple formula is to take a celebrity by
surprise, and tell his or her life story through friends and family.
Thames, recently bought by Pearson, owner of the Financial Times, has been
attracting audiences of 12m to 14m for the programme. But ITV said yesterday
it felt unable to commit itself to the long-term deal that Thames was
seeking. The production company is already selling Pounds 40m of programmes
to ITV this year.
'ITV is keen to commission more programmes which appeal to young up-market
viewers, as well as to its established audience,' said the ITV Network
Centre. It is nudging its channel up-market at the very time that the BBC is
rediscovering the need to appeal to a broad audience to protect its
universally imposed licence fee.
The Thames deal also involves developing new drama and comedy ideas for the
BBC.
Mr Alan Yentob, controller of BBC 1, said he was luring a number of top
performers back from ITV in deals with independent producers.
They include comedy stars Rowan Atkinson and Dave Allen. SelecTv, producers
of the hit show Birds of a Feather, will be making a new comedy about a
hen-pecked husband who finds romance when he enters a 1940s time warp.
</TEXT>
