<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / Rabin condemned for shelling: Clinton appeals to all parties
to halt conflict in southern Lebanon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE and MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NABATIYEH, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ISRAEL'S prime minister Yitzhak Rabin faced heavy criticism last night both
from his closest allies abroad and within his cabinet at home for the
four-day bombardment of southern Lebanon which has forced nearly 250,000
civilians to flee their homes.
The US, stepping up its efforts to end the fighting, criticised Israel for
targeting civilians and urged Syria to do more to stop the conflict, while
Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, United Nations secretary-general, condemned
Israel's attack.
As Mr Rabin's Labour-led administration appeared increasingly isolated
internationally, a political crisis was looming in Israel as two parties
backing the coalition government strongly opposed continuing the offensive.
Two cabinet ministers, speaking on television on behalf of the left-wing
Meretz party which has 12 MPs, called for the shelling to cease immediately
and said they opposed Mr Rabin's objective of driving villagers out of
southern Lebanon. Unruly scenes also erupted in parliament, and an Arab MP,
who repeatedly harangued Mr Rabin, was expelled from the Knesset. The
five-strong Arab group of MPs was considering its future support for Mr
Rabin.
Mr Rabin pledged, however, to continue the offensive until Israel's security
interests were achieved, and said refugees fleeing the Israeli bombardment
of their villages would not be allowed to return home until rocket attacks
by pro-Iranian Hizbollah fighters ceased.
Yesterday marked the first direct criticism from the US.
President Bill Clinton called on Hizbollah to stop rocket attacks on Israel,
but also demanded that Israel stop its blitz of villages in southern Lebanon
which has left more than 100 people dead. The president also urged Syria 'to
go from showing restraint to being an active participant to try to stop the
fighting'.
US State Department officials were unusually severe in their criticism.
'It's clear that there have been attacks directed against civilians,' said
Mr Mike McCurry, the State Department spokesman. He called the flood of
refugees 'deeply disturbing'. But he acknowledged there had also been
attacks directed against civilians in northern Israel.
The crushing bombardment and air attacks on the region continued for a
fourth day, as Israel directed its heavy artillery fire to the area south of
Tyre and shelled further north to broaden the area it effectively controls.
In Nabatiyeh, a town which has been under sustained attack, remaining
residents were trapped without transport and with dwindling food supplies.
Mr Rabin yesterday called on Syria to use its influence to curb the Islamic
fighters and said a dialogue with Damascus would open when Mr Warren
Christopher, US secretary of state, visits the region at the weekend.
Mr Rabin refused to say how long the operation would last. 'We are steadfast
in our decision to continue to act to achieve our aims,' he said.
Syria called for international pressure to force Israel to stop its attacks,
which official newspapers described as barbaric and a threat to regional
peace. President Elias Hrawi of Lebanon said the country was united against
the Israeli occupation.
An Israeli army spokesman in the border town of Metulla said that by
yesterday evening more than 14,500 shells had been fired into southern
Lebanon. Hizbollah fighters, massively overwhelmed by superior Israeli
firepower, continued to harass Israeli forces, launching 28 Katyusha
rockets.
Anger of South Lebanon pours into Beirut Page 3
Editorial Comment Page 15
</TEXT>
