<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ITV's imported National Geographic series showing macho feats of endurance,
Voyager, today tells the story of a journey by eight young men in an open
boat, a replica of a 12th century Celtic galley. The plan was to retrace a
journey made 700 years previously, from the west coast of Scotland to the
Faroes (7.30).
Is BS 5750 a means of turning British industry into a world beater, or a bit
of bureaucratic nonsense? In Business Matters Nick Clarke looks at the
effects of the international standard for quality introduced by the British
Standards Institute (8.00 BBC2).
There have been few original British programmes among the welter of repeats
this summer, and most have been mediocre, so you wonder whether inclusion in
the summer schedule is an admission of low quality. However, Thicker Than
Water, a mini-series on BBC1, has been adapted by
Trevor Preston and stars Theresa Russell and Jonathan Pryce, so it should be
worth a look.
BBC1 covers the declaration at Christchurch in By-election Special (12.15).
</TEXT>
