<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / Getting on the aid map is only half the battle: Meeting
government criteria for regional financial assistance can be a tricky but
rewarding business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SKIRMISH between parts of Britain vying for assisted-area status is
over. Now the fight for the grants it unlocks can begin.
From this weekend the government's new assisted areas map, announced last
Friday, comes into effect, entitling companies in parts of London and on the
east and south coasts of England for the first time to regional financial
assistance from the Department of Trade and Industry.
Many company directors in the new assisted areas are aware there could be
something in this for them - the DTI received nearly 2,000 submissions
pleading to be on the new map, which covers 34 per cent of Britain's working
population.
But many newly assisted areas, and companies within them, face a steep
learning curve if they are to obtain full benefit from a grants regime which
has no automatic entitlements and no fixed grant rate.
The message to new contenders from successful applicants in north-east
England - parts of which have been assisted since regional aid began in the
1930s - is encouraging.
'It was a good return on the effort,' said Mr Neil Heppell, finance director
of Tyneside-based Freudenberg Technical Products, which was offered Pounds
900,000 in regional selective assistance last year towards a Pounds 5m
project.
Mr Peter Cowin, co-founder of Seabait, a Northumberland fishing-bait
producer, said: 'The DTI were very helpful and processed things very
quickly.' He has made two succesful applications for regional assistance
grants totalling Pounds 45,000.
Inevitably, not all applicants succeed. In 1991-92, offers of assistance
totalled Pounds 210.5m, against applications for Pounds 368.5m. The DTI
expects to offer about the same amount of regional assistance grants this
year.
Small companies in assisted areas can also apply for regional enterprise
grants of up to Pounds 15,000 for investment projects, or up to Pounds
25,000 for innovation projects. These grants totalled Pounds 13.7m in
1991-92.
To maximise the chances of getting assistance, it is important to understand
not just the DTI's criteria but the thinking behind them.
On average, awards in development areas run at between 15 per cent and 20
per cent of the fixed capital cost of a project; in intermediate areas, the
average is 10 per cent. The main criteria are:
The project must show viability.
It must create or safeguard jobs.
It must have a regional or national benefit.
It must need the grant.
Assistance must be the minimum required to enable the project to go ahead
and be funding of last resort.
Arguing a project's case may be complex; applicants must decide whether to
go it alone, enlist the help of accountants or auditors, seek advice from
enterprise agencies and similar bodies or turn to one of the teams of
consultants specialising in UK and European grants and loans applications.
Grants are good business for consultants - within days of the annoucement of
the new map, Eurofi, which says it is Europe's largest independent grants
consultancy, had sent offers of help in applying for assistance to targeted
companies throughout Britain's newly assisted areas.
Mindful that many companies resent paying for no certain result, many
consultants work largely on a success fee basis, geared to the grant
obtained. 'No duck, no dinner,' said Mr Vince Taylor, one of the accountants
in Coopers &amp; Lybrand's 15-strong specialist grants team, which helped 10 of
the newly assisted areas to lobby successfully for their place on the map.
Officially the DTI has no view on the use of consultants by applicants.
Privately, some officials find reputable, experienced consultants helpful
while others have mixed feelings, especially if the consultants' fee is
linked to the size of grant obtained.
Mr Jim Driscoll, responsible for grants and inward investment at Coopers &amp;
Lybrand, warns against any premature actions, such as taking an option on
land, which suggests firm commitment to a project.
Mr Driscoll says applicants often find it difficult to understand their
project must be commercially viable, yet need grant aid to proceed. 'Need
means the need to secure the project in that location,' he said.
If all this sounds daunting, potential applicants can take heart from Mr
Cowin. Applications for assistance are easy, he says, compared with the
Euro-grants maze. 'That's a nightmare.'
</TEXT>
