<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / Matisse boosts Christies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SALES AT Christies Inter-national, the fine-art auctioneer, rose 16 per cent
to Pounds 683m in the 1992-93 season which ends this month. But in dollar
terms - major works of art are valued in US dollars - the gain on the year
was only 1 per cent, to Dollars 1.05bn.
Mr David Tyler, finance director, said yesterday: 'We feel generally
encouraged. There has been a slow consolidation, and the mood has improved
in the last six months.' However, the art market still has a long way to go
to approach the heights of 1989-90.
Nine works of art fetched prices above Dollars 5m, compared with six in the
1991-92 season. Six were Impressionist or post-Impressionist pictures. The
sums included Dollars 14.5m for a Matisse and Dollars 12.1m and Dollars 9.6m
for Monet paintings. Two others which fetched more than Dollars 5m were Old
Masters.
The most encouraging factor was the return of some major buyers for
post-1870 pictures, which were at the centre of the rise in the art market
in the late 1980s.
The auctioneer's sales in New York were up 28 per cent - 12 per cent in
dollar terms - compared with a sterling rise of 10 per cent in the UK.
</TEXT>
