<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / Councils face accounts shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW RULES requiring councils to keep registers of fixed assets will
revolutionise local-authority accounting and are expected to improve
financial management.
A new statement of recommended practice, approved last week by the
Accounting Standards Board, means that councils will have to show the value
of property - such as schools and equipment - in their balance sheets at
current cost and recognise the cost of using such assets.
'As local authorities become more like commercial organisations they have
got to manage their assets properly,' said Mr Martin Evans, head of the
technical division at the Chartered Institute of Public Finance and
Accountancy, which describes the changes as the most radical in
local-authority accounting for 100 years. 'Many authorities are asset-rich
but do not know the value of the assets they hold,' he said.
Most councils are obliged to implement the changes by the 1994-95 financial
year.
The move to capital accounting will also help comparisons between public and
private-sector services in the move towards compulsory competitive tendering
by local authorities.
Indications are that few will be enthusiastic about the changes. Mr Martin
Pilgrim, of the Labour-controlled Association of Metropolitan Authorities,
said many councils were concerned about the cost of the exercise. 'Although
it is inevitable that our present practices have to change, many authorities
will not see this as positive or helpful.'
Mr Evans said that in some respects the new statement goes further than
current practice in the private sector. It requires that fixed assets be
included in the balance sheet at current value and be revalued at regular
intervals. Depreciation charges will then be charged in their accounts based
on these amounts.
