<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / Government 'vindicated' over Swans bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NATIONAL Audit Office report into the bids for a helicopter carrier
order, which left Tyneside shipbuilder Swan Hunter facing closure,
vindicates the government's decision to award the contract to the rival
bidder, Mr Neville Trotter, Tory MP for Tynemouth, claimed yesterday.
According to Mr Trotter, the report from the government's spending watchdog,
to be made public today, says the main factor in the award was price. Both
bids were assessed by the Ministry of Defence as technically acceptable and
with the same overall level of risk.
According to the report, said Mr Trotter: 'The advice given to the ministers
on both technical and commercial aspects was correct.'
The report, he said, confirms that at the final stage, Swan Hunter bid
Pounds 210m while its rival, a consortium of Cumbria-based VSEL and the
Kvaerner Govan merchant shipyard on the Clyde, bid Pounds 139m - Pounds 71m
less.
It also says technical consultants appointed by the NAO had concluded that
assessment of the offers was thorough and that both bids were treated
fairly.
This apparently contradicts claims from Swan Hunter campaigners that the
MoD's final bidding process was biased against the company. But, according
to the disclosures, the report does confirm claims that VSEL in effect
subsidised its bid.
Mr Trotter said the report states: 'VSEL opted to take the risk of
supporting their bid significantly from the company's resources.' He added
that it says that VSEL did not want its bid figure made public.
The report is the result of an inquiry launched after Swan Hunter went into
receivership in mid-May, two days after losing the order.
According to Mr Trotter, the report also refutes claims that the bidders
were offering different ships - 'a Rolls-Royce or a Lada', as one Swans
campaigner put it. It says the consortium vessel is a warship built to
appropriate standards, which it describes as 'a cost-effective solution
without prejudicing personnel safety, financial requirements or quality'.
Mr Trotter said the report discloses that Swans increased its bid price at
the final stage by Pounds 36m, including Pounds 12m for extra overheads, at
the suggestion of GEC, then negotiating to take over the company.
Tyneside Labour MPs Mr Steve Byers and Mr Nick Brown yesterday met senior
management of Bremer Vulkan, the German shipbuilding and general engineering
group which was one of companies considering whether to bid for Swans.
As part of the campaign to retain shipbuilding on the Tyne, union leaders
met Mr Tim Sainsbury, the industry minister, to discuss the prospects of
Swan Hunter securing European intervention funding subsidy. Mr Trotter was
meeting European Commission officials in Brussels last night for talks on
prospects for Swan Hunter.
</TEXT>
