<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / Mines at risk as bidders stay away
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOPES OF RESCUE for a large number of pits discarded by British Coal were
fading last night after it emerged that private-sector companies were
interested in mining only one of the first four on offer.
British Coal said it had received bids, accompanied by bonds of Pounds
50,000, for three of the four pits. However, in two cases, Cotgrave and
Silverhill in Nottinghamshire, the proposals involved only the surface
assets of the mines and there were no plans for continuing mining at them.
The Union of Democratic Mineworkers has already announced the formation of a
joint venture with Vista Partnership in an attempt to create up to 900 jobs
for former miners at Cotgrave and Silverhill. The plan is to build domestic
waste recycling and disposal facilities on the sites.
The one pit of the four where mining may still continue is Easington in
Durham. RJB Mining is thought to be among the bidders and may be the only
one.
Yesterday's developments mean British Coal is likely to move swiftly to
close finally the Bolsover mine in Derbyshire, the last of the four to be
offered in the first batch. Another 15 pits are on offer with bidding
deadlines still open.
Industry observers believe it is unlikely that more than six of the 19 pits
will be mined, although more than 300 initial expressions of interest have
been received by British Coal.
</TEXT>
