<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / CBI backs pensions for all at 65
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Confederation of British Industry, the employers group, yesterday urged
the government to stop dithering and raise women's retirement age to 65.
It said: 'The present indecision is causing real concern in the business
community. It is time they made up their minds. A decision needs to be
announced soon with a lengthy phasing-in so that the position of women
currently planning to retire at 60 is fully protected.'
A survey by William M Mercer, actuarial consultant, for the CBI concluded
that lowering men's retirement ages to match those of women would increase
existing occupational pension liabilities by Pounds 21bn. It would also add
Pounds 2bn a year to the cost of offering the existing level of occupational
pension benefit.
Mr Howard Davies, CBI director-general, said: 'Faced with such costs, more
firms would have to consider cutting the pensions offered or moving away
from pensions linked to final salaries.'
Many European countries have equal retirement ages for men and women, but
while British women are generally eligible to receive pensions from age 60,
most men must wait until 65.
A government white paper on pensions policy has already been delayed and it
not likely to be published until the autumn.
The National Association of Pension Funds, the industry trade association,
has urged the government to make a speedy decision.
Mr Davies said: 'The present indecision is causing real concern in the
business community. A decision needs to be announced soon with a lengthy
phasing-in (period).'
He argued that if the pensionable age were reduced, the government would be
stepping 'out of line with international trends.'
Mr Davies said: 'The Germans plan to move to an equal pension age of 65 by
2012 and the Italians by 2016, while the Americans are moving by stages to
equalisation at 67 by 2027.
'The UK government should similarly make it clear its intention to move over
a period of years to an equalised state pension age of 65.'
</TEXT>
