<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / Clarke to look at tax increases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OPTIONS for tax increases in the November Budget will be discussed tomorrow
by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, at a private meeting in his official
country home at Dorneywood, Buckinghamshire, Peter Marsh writes.
Mr Clarke will talk about the Budget with other Treasury ministers and
senior officials. The group is expected to consider proposals for increasing
taxes from April, as part of the effort to bring down the rising budget
deficit - expected to be Pounds 50bn this financial year. Any tax increases
would come on top of the Pounds 6.7bn of tax rises which have already been
announced.
The meeting will review the latest unpublished Treasury forecasts that gross
domestic product this year will grow slightly faster than the 1.25 per cent
predicted by officials in March. However, in recent weeks signs have emerged
that the solid growth of the first half of the year might not be sustained
in the second half, owing to weak UK demand and a deterioration in export
markets in continental Europe.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
