<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / BBC sets 'robust' reform targets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BBC's governors yesterday set targets for the corporation for next year,
including sharper coverage of science and technology and ensuring
interviewees are treated with courtesy.
In their first annual review of the BBC's performance the governors also
said they would require assurance that financial controls are robust.
They want to see that 'managers are using the newly provided financial
information to achieve further efficiency gains and that no new bureaucracy
is emerging to replace the one so recently dismantled'.
The governors said that the diversion of resources from bureaucracy and
overheads to creative programme-making must continue because it was at the
heart of the reforms now being introduced.
Having defined their role for the first time as 'trustees for the public',
in future the governors' job will include ensuring that the BBC's strategy
reflects the public's needs and interests, ensuring compliance with
regulations and guidelines and, for the first time, publishing a regular
programme complaints bulletin.
The review says that in the past three years the BBC has cut its overheads
by a net 5.2 per cent a year and costs in the resource departments were cut
by 2.5 per cent a year, releasing an extra Pounds 65m for programme-making.
BBC Annual Review. Available from bookshops. Pounds 3.99.
</TEXT>
