FT  29 JUL 93 / Police arrest Nadir tax inspector
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A TAX investigator involved in inquiries into the financial affairs of Mr
Asil Nadir, the fugitive tycoon, was arrested yesterday by detectives
probing 'alleged corruption'.
Mr Michael Allcock and his wife Sally were taken from their home in
Chelmsford, Essex, to London for questioning by Metropolitan and City of
London Fraud Squad officers.
The couple were released on police bail and ordered to report back to
Holborn police station in October, Scotland Yard said.
Mr Allcock is the tax inspector accused by Mr Michael Mates, the former
Northern Ireland minister, of 'improper collusion' with the Serious Fraud
Office.
Mr Mates, who resigned over the Nadir affair last month, said that Mr
Allcock tipped off the SFO. However Mr Allcock, in an interview with the
Financial Times earlier this month, insisted instead that he had reported
his suspicions about Mr Nadir, who jumped bail in May, to the Stock
Exchange.
Mr Allcock was suspended in September as head of the Revenue's Special
Office 2, its crack investigative unit, on full pay pending a Fraud Squad
investigation following an internal inquiry, not related to the Nadir
affair, by Revenue officials.
In the FT interview he gave details of how he worked closely with the
exchange in its investigation of Mr Nadir's financial affairs and those of
Swiss companies believed to be fronting for him.
The exchange has acknowledged that it received corroborative information
from the Revenue that led it to ask the SFO to carry out the first of its
raids on Mr Nadir's companies.
</TEXT>
