FT  29 JUL 93 / Media groups to join lottery bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CARLTON Communications and Associated Newspapers are about to join the
Granada-led consortium planning to bid for the licence to operate the new
national lottery.
An announcement is expected today that the groups have joined the
consortium, The Great British Lottery Company.
Carlton, which holds the London weekday ITV licence, and Associated
Newspapers, which publishes the Daily Mail and the Mail on Sunday, are each
believed to be taking a 10 per cent stake in the venture.
The main members of the consortium are Granada, the leisure group, and the
Vodafone Group, the mobile telecommunications concern, each with 35 per
cent. Hambros, the merchant bank that put the consortium together, also has
a 10 per cent stake. Mr Gerry Robinson, chief executive of Granada, is
executive chairman of the consortium.
The new shareholders should help to make the consortium one of the leading
contenders for the lottery, which is due to be launched late next year or
early in 1995.
The lottery, which could eventually have annual revenues of Pounds
3bn-Pounds 5bn, is designed to raise money for charity, the arts, sport,
national heritage and celebrating the millennium. The national lottery bill
is due to receive royal assent in October.
So far, the lottery licence's other main contenders include NM Rothschild,
the merchant bank, in a joint venture with Tattersall's, the Australian
company which runs the state lottery in Victoria; the Rank Organisation; and
a consortium put together by GTECH of the US, which supplies lottery
equipment and runs lotteries all over the world. Bids are also expected from
the leading football pools companies Littlewoods and Vernons, part of
Ladbroke's.
The National Heritage Department is expected to announce by the middle of
next month the appointment of a regulatory adviser, who would also probably
become director-general designate of the Office of the National Lottery.
</TEXT>
