<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / Efim deal takes shape
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM and LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE EC Commission has reached preliminary agreement with Italy that paves
the way for the Italian government to begin disbursing L7,000bn (Pounds
2.9bn) of funds earmarked for creditors of Efim, the state industrial
holding.
The agreement came too close to the summer recess for the full details to be
worked out. This means the Italian government is unlikely to be able to
begin consider disbursements to banks and suppliers before late September.
The deal has been struck at a 'political' level by Mr Beniamino Andreatta,
the Italian foreign minister, with Mr Karel Van Miert, the EC commissioner
in charge of competition. Although neither side will admit as much, the
agreement is part of a trade-off in Italy's acrimonious dispute with
Brussels over state subsidies - and particularly those for Ilva, the
loss-making state steel group.
On Tuesday, Mr Andreatta softened Italy's stance over Ilva and agreed to
withdraw plans to write off Ecu4bn (Pounds 3bn) incurred by the steel group.
The Italians have made no secret of their view that Brussels has been
blocking an Efim agreement to exert pressure in the Ilva affair.
Italy now has until August 14 to present fresh proposals for Ilva's future,
which will be studied in late September. Until the EC is satisfied with the
Ilva plan, it could go slow on formalising an agreement on Efim.
Efim was placed in liquidation last July with L18,000bn worth of debts split
roughly equally between banks and suppliers. Foreign banks are owed over
L3,500bn.
The Italian parliament approved disbursement of L9,000bn over three months
to Efim creditors; but since then Brussels has only given the go-ahead for
L2,000bn to the defence side of the state holding.
Mr Van Miert blocked the funds on the grounds that repayment of Efim's
accumulated debts represented a form of subsidy. The Italian government
argued that it was legally bound to honour Efim debts which amounted to
sovereign debt.
The outline agreement envisages the Italian government being able to honour
Efim debt accumulated at the time of liquidation, plus subsequent interest
and refinancing arrangements. The government will be placing L4,000bn in the
1994 budget to cover the further cost of the liquidation.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Ente Partecipazioni e Finanziamento Industria
    Manifatturiera.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ITZ  Italy, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6719 Holding Companies, NEC.
</IN>
