<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / EC backs de Larosiere for EBRD: Italy and Denmark withdraw
their candidates at last minute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON, East Europe Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 12-nation European Community reached a last-minute consensus last night
to propose Mr Jacques de Larosiere of France as the EC candidate for the
presidency of the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD).
The agreement, announced in a letter to EC leaders by Mr Phillipe Maystadt,
the Belgian minister of finance, came at the end of an extra week of
protracted negotiations between EC members in which the EBRD candidacy was
part of wider horse-trading over the siting of the future European central
bank.
At the last moment Italy and Denmark withdrew their candidates - Mr Giuliano
Amato, the former Italian prime minister, and Mr Henning Christophersen, the
Danish EC commissioner - although the Italian decision in particular is
believed to have been fiercely contested by politicians in Rome angry at
French domination of key international financial institutions.
The nomination of Mr de Larosiere, governor of the Bank of France and a
former managing director of the IMF, does not mean he will automatically
become the next president of the EBRD in succession to the disgraced former
president, Mr Jacques Attali. The final choice will depend on the outcome of
the complex two-tier voting system in which the G7 countries have a weighted
vote proportional to their shareholdings, while the 57 governors of the
bank, representing shareholder governments from both east and west, have one
vote each plus an additional two votes wielded by the EC and the European
Investment Bank.
Neither the US, which is entitled to 10 per cent of the votes as the largest
single shareholder, nor Japan, another G7 member with an 8.5 per cent voting
share, have formally stated their preference. But Mr Lloyd Bentsen, US
Treasury secretary, hinted strongly at an OECD meeting earlier this month
that the US would vote with the EC.
The EC consensus practically eliminates the possibility that the fourth
candidate, Mr Leszek Balcerowicz, the former Polish finance minister, could
be chosen to lead the bank which was set up two years ago to foster
investment in the former communist states of east Europe.
Day-to-day running of the bank over the last few months has been largely in
the hands of Mr Ron Freeman, the American who heads the merchant banking
division of the EBRD. He is expected to continue as the effective chief
executive of the bank under de Larosiere.
</TEXT>
