<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / Tory party workers braced for by-election defeat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSERVATIVE party workers in Christchurch were bracing themselves for
defeat in today's by-election, as last-minute campaigning drew to an end in
the Dorset seaside constituency.
But with all parties reporting that a significant proportion of voters
canvassed were still wavering, the size of the expected anti-Tory swing
remained uncertain.
A victory for the Liberal Democrats in the former Conservative stronghold
would cut the government's overall majority in the House of Commons to 17.
A disaster for the Tories in the constituency they held by more than 23,000
in the general election has been so widely predicted that the political
damage has to some extent been discounted. Even so, a large majority for Mrs
Diana Maddock, the Liberal Democrat candidate, would be a fresh humiliation
for Mr John Major's beleaguered administration.
The government's efforts to put the difficulties of the past year behind it
were dealt a further setback by a national opinion poll which showed support
for the Tories at 27 per cent - their lowest rating since December 1981.
Only 19 per cent of those questioned were satisfied with the prime
minister's performance, while almost three-quarters were dissatisfied.
The Mori survey, in today's Times also showed rising support for the Liberal
Democrats at 25 per cent, while Labour was on 44 per cent. The polling was
taken between 22-26 July with a sample of 1,689 people.
In Christchurch, Sir Norman Fowler, the Tory party chairman, sought to
capitalise on the recent signs of economic recovery.
But party workers brought in to support Mr Rob Hayward, the Tory candidate,
appeared to be pinning some hope on discontented Conservatives abstaining.
One or two activists even conceded that their task was to contain the
Liberal Democrat majority rather than win the seat.
Although the government's plans to impose value added tax on domestic fuel
have been a significant reason for the loss of support in the constituency,
Sir Norman ruled out any changes in VAT policy after the by-election.
Labour, widely predicted to come a poor third in the vote, said it hoped
that the growing anti-Tory sentiment in the area would help Labour to secure
greater support in the south in the next election.
A total of 14 candidates are standing in the by-election, which was caused
by the death of Conservative MP, Mr Robert Adley.
