<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / Bundesbank move raises hopes of discount rate cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BUNDESBANK yesterday cut the cost of lending short term funds to
commercial banks, raising expectations that it would reduce its official
rates at a council meeting today and quell growing currency tensions inside
the European exchange rate mechanism.
The German central bank's cut in its repo rate from 7.15 per cent to 6.95
per cent was slightly larger than currency dealers had expected, and raised
hopes that it would today cut the internationally sensitive discount rate,
which sets the floor for all German money market rates.
The bank cut its discount rate to 6.75 per cent from 7.25 per cent on July
2. The Lombard rate was lowered from 8.50 per cent to 8.25 per cent at the
same time.
Yesterday's repo rate cut helped quell tensions in the ERM at the start of
European trading, including heavy selling of the Spanish peseta and
Portuguese escudo, and continued pressure on the French franc.
Analysts were uncertain about what decision the Bundesbank would have to
take today to quell tensions in the ERM during the remaining summer weeks.
In UK financial markets, there was strong speculation that a large cut in
German interest rates today might allow the British government to lower base
rates, currently at 6 per cent.
Some dealers in sterling interest rate markets were confident base rates
would be cut within weeks. That speculation pushed sterling  1/4 pfennig
down against the D-Mark to close in London at DM2.5675. It was little
changed at DM2.5687 in New York. The Bundesbank meeting, the last before the
summer recess, will be the most keenly watched event in currency markets
since the ERM crisis of last September.
There was a strong assumption in the London market that the Bundesbank would
cut its discount rate by  1/2 a percentage point. Some analysts believed
rates would need to ease  3/4 of a percentage point for France and other ERM
countries to have an opportunity to lower the cost of short term borrowing.
There were fears that the Bundesbank was giving priority to domestic price
stability rather than the ERM. 'If we do not cut the discount rate, then the
French franc might go the same way as sterling, and leave the system,' a
German economist said. 'The view will be that the Bundesbank is not
committed to ERM, or to the second phase of the Maastricht treaty.'
Yesterday's cut in the repo rate halted intense selling of the Spanish
peseta, which fell by about 2 per cent against the D-Mark in early European
trading. There was also heavy selling of the Portuguese escudo, which fell
to a historic low against the D-Mark, and neared its ERM floor against the
German currency. Both currencies recovered after the Bundesbank's action,
the Spanish peseta closing at Pta80.41 against the German currency. The
French franc rallied to close at FFr3.405, amid a slight softening in French
money market interest rates.
Gilts sale confounds, Page 6
Editorial comment, Page 15
Government bonds, Page 26
Currencies, Page 29
