<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 93 / International Company News: Shares slide after Data General
loss worsens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Data General fell yesterday after the US minicomputer manufacturer
announced it had fallen further into the red during its third quarter.
The company lost Dollars 16.4m, or 47 cents a share, between April and June,
against a Dollars 11.7m loss in the same period of 1992 and a Dollars 7.6m
loss in the first three months of this year.
The latest losses were more than twice as large as analysts had expected,
pushing Data General shares Dollars  1/8 lower to Dollars 8 1/2 at the close
on the New York Stock Exchange.
Mr Ronald Skates, president and chief executive, blamed 'the weak worldwide
economy, particularly in the European marketplace, and industry-wide
competitive pricing pressures' for the poor results.
Overall revenues during the quarter totalled Dollars 252.4m, down from
Dollars 259.2m, although the decline was entirely due to the negative impact
of changes in foreign exchange rates.
Revenues from traditional proprietary minicomputer products continued to
decline. The company, however, is shifting away from proprietary products to
open systems based upon industry standards. But once again, strong sales of
its open systems products failed to stem the losses.
Mr Skates said the success of the open systems line of products reinforced
their belief the open systems strategy was correct.
</TEXT>
