<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 93 / International Company News: Gerstner sees no place for a
'vision' at IBM - Chairman says priority is to get the company 'rightsized'
as soon as possible
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Lou Gerstner, IBM chairman and chief executive, said yesterday:
'Rightsizing IBM as quickly as possible, to restore the company to
profitability is my number one priority.'
In his first substantive public comments since joining the troubled computer
company on April 1, Mr Gerstner made clear that he had no 'grand master
strategy' to turn IBM around.
'There has been a lot of speculation that I'm going to deliver a 'vision' of
(the future of) IBM,' he said.
'The last thing IBM needs right now is a vision. What IBM needs right now is
a series of very tough-minded, market-driven (and) highly effective
strategies that deliver performance in the marketplace, and shareholder
value.'
IBM's primary problem is its cost structure, Mr Gerstner stressed at press
conferences in New York after presenting his company's results.
'In the last three months we have all been focused on getting that problem
behind us, of getting rightsized as quickly as possible,' he said.
'The management team feels that we need to get this (restructuring) behind
us as fast as we can.
'IBM's problem is very simple. We sell about Dollars 65bn worth of products
per year. At the end of the day we don't make any money.
'We don't have a problem with our products, our services or our technology -
we have a problem with our cost structure.
'My second priority for the company is to win the battle in the customer's
premises,' Mr Gerstner continued.
'Our prices have become more competitive and our technology is the best in
the industry, but we do not have a monopoly.' IBM must intensify its
competitiveness, he said.
Identifying which products and technologies represent the best prospects for
growth, comes third on Mr Gerstner's list, although he mentioned
microelectronics and multimedia as two areas that have his attention.
IBM would not hesitate to pull out of segments of the computer market in
which it was not either a technology leader or making profits, Mr Gerstner
said.
'Nowhere in any of our minds, certainly not mine, is there a view that IBM's
strategy is to be all things to all people, and to participate in all
elements of the information technology business,' he said. 'We are not in
any way pursuing that as an objective.'
Employee morale was a serious concern, Mr Gerstner said. Morale had suffered
as a result of continuing lay-offs and losses, the chairman acknowledged.
'Morale is not good in parts of the company, we have got to get behind this
Chinese water torture we are going through,' he said.
However, in spite of the attention that has been given to whether Mr
Gerstner will restructure IBM's management, he expressed little interest in
the subject.
'I'm spending a lot of time on customer issues, on technologies, on
employees and the economics of the business, and I don't really care what
committees we have.
'Process is not what we're going to talk about. Performance is what we are
going to talk about.
'We will never stop fixing IBM. Because of the nature of the business, we
will be constantly renewing this organisation and our challenge is to get
that renewal process continuous without bumps and starts.
'That is the requirement of any company in the '90s, but more so in the
information technology industry where the pace of change is so rapid.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>International Business Machines Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
