<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 93 / Cabinet backs end to public sector pay ceiling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR KENNETH CLARKE, the chancellor, has won cabinet backing for his plan to
scrap next year the rigid 1.5 per cent ceiling for public-sector pay
settlements.
But the government is expected to replace the formula with tight cash limits
on the pay bills of the main Whitehall departments.
The expectation among ministers is that the overall wage costs of the public
sector will not be allowed to grow by more than about 2 per cent.
With the annual public spending negotiations now under way Mr Clarke argued
that a second year of rigid pay restraint would increase the risk of
damaging pay rises when the ceiling was lifted.
That view, shared by Mr John Major, has been accepted by colleagues serving
on the cabinet committee charged with meeting the government's spending
targets.
The decision has heightened concern within Whitehall that the government
will be unable to avoid significant cuts in capital spending programmes
unless it replaces the present formula with a cash limit.
The Department of the Environment in particular has warned that it may be
impossible to hold down local authority pay without a clear signal on the
need for continuing restraint.
The Treasury's public spending targets allow for growth in spending of less
than 1 per cent a year in real terms for the next three financial years.
In spite of a series of negotiations between Mr Michael Portillo, the chief
secretary to the Treasury, and the ministers responsible for the main
spending departments, bids for funds in the 1994-95 financial year are still
several billion pounds above the Treasury's Pounds 254bn cash target.
Few of the spending ministers have been willing to concede any reductions
ahead of the autumn, when the cabinet committee will examine line-by-line
all the principal Whitehall budgets.
</TEXT>
