<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 93 / German inflation boosts rate cut hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GERMAN interest rates could be cut further this week even though inflation
has increased again, economists in Germany argued yesterday.
The cost of living in western Germany rose at an annual rate of 4.3 per cent
in the month to mid-July, compared with 4.2 per cent in June, the federal
statistics office reported.
Mr Martin Hufner, chief economist at the Bayerische Vereinsbank, noted that
in the previous three months consumer prices had increased at a 'moderate'
annual rate of 3.1 per cent, thanks partly to cheaper oil.
Although money supply growth was still exceeding the Bundesbank's target
range the rate of expansion was weakening detectably, and if this continued
there was a good chance it would return to within the range of 4.5 per cent
to 6.5 per cent annualised growth fixed by the central bank. The broad M3
money supply measure in June grew at an annualised rate of 7.1 per cent.
Although the consensus yesterday was that there was more than an even chance
of a reduction in German rates, few expect a cut of more than half a
percentage point in the key discount rate, currently 6.75 per cent.
Dr Hufner added that renewed tension in the European monetary system was an
important further argument for an interest rate cut at the central bank's
meeting tomorrow, the last before the summer break.
The Bundesbank announced yesterday it would accept variable bids from
commercial banks for short-term funds in its weekly money market operation.
Some dealers believe the cost of borrowing short-term funds should come down
today by about 0.15 percentage points to 7 per cent.
However in the ERM the Spanish peseta, Portuguese escudo and Danish krone
came under some selling pressure yesterday afternoon.
The French franc weakened slightly against the D-Mark.
Germany's July inflation figure, which matched most forecasts, was based on
preliminary calculations from four important states.
Currencies, Page 33
World stocks, Page 39
