<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 93 / Observer: Fidelity
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
What do Fidel Castro and an expensive, brightly coloured woolly jumper have
in common? Not much at the moment but perhaps a lot in the future.
For Benetton, the shrinking violet of the Italian clothes business which
recently opened a number of branches in Cuba, has asked the ageing dictator
to become the figurehead of its planned 'research centre' to be based at
Treviso in Italy.
The letter from Luciano Benetton - the company's head - is a very odd
document, probably one of the last flattering missives Castro can expect to
receive.
It invites Castro to become a 'teacher of revolution' at the new
institution. 'A school of this kind needs a teacher. I thought of you
because many of us have not forgotten the idealistic vision you offered your
country . . .'
'It's not a joke,' says a Benetton pr. 'Castro's political cycle may be
coming to an end but he did do an enormous amount to inspire the youth of
his country and he would be ideal for an avant-garde school.'
What next? Kim Il Sung signs up for Volkswagen?
</TEXT>
