<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 93 / Letter: Privatisation can improve forest management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr TERRY ARTHUR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, James Buxton's article on forest privatisation ('When money grows on
trees', July 20) concludes that privatisation may be no more successful than
the Forestry Commission at 'balancing commercial needs with environmental
and leisure interests'.
Although it is wrong to imply that environmental and leisure interests
cannot be commercial, there are certainly conflicting interests to balance.
However, both reason and experience suggest strongly that privatisation
would indeed be more successful.
Briefly, public sector management is a zero sum game in which opposing
political 'constituents' and lobbyists are appeased or otherwise. Private
sector management replaces conflict by co-operation and cost sharing. The
largest private landowner in the US, the International Paper Company, not
only practices commercial lumbering but also runs profitable wild life and
recreation programmes in many states, leasing more than 1m acres in the
southern states for such purposes.
Terry Arthur,
23 St Mary's Street,
Stamford, Lincs PE9 2DG
</TEXT>
