<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Top judge backs right to jury trial
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD TAYLOR, the Lord Chief Justice, said yesterday he was opposed to
abolition of the defendant's right to choose trial by jury.
Removing the defendant's right to elect for jury trial in cases which can be
tried either by magistrates or at the Crown Court was the most controversial
of 352 recommendations made by the Royal Commission on Criminal Justice
earlier this month.
Giving his first public response to the commission's report at a conference
in London, Lord Taylor said it was essential not only for justice to be done
but for those concerned to have confidence in the process.
'We must have regard to our history, our culture and the perception of many
that trial by jury is a fundamental right,' he said.
If limits were to be placed on the right it would be better to increase the
categories of less serious cases which should automatically by tried by
magistrates. This might involve removing the right for low-value thefts, for
example. But this was 'surely preferable to the socially divisive regime
which may well result from the commission's more sweeping proposal'.
The Lord Chief Justice said he welcomed the commission's report in general.
</TEXT>
