<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Tories see image boost in PM's
strong words
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR TORY party figures insisted yesterday that the publication of full
transcripts of private conversations in which Mr John Major swore and made
derogatory remarks about colleagues would enhance his standing rather than
damage it.
There had been fears that Mr Major's remarks were so much at odds with the
Conservatives' public calls for unity following the split within the party
over Maastricht, that they would add to the impression of Tory disarray.
But party officials said that telephone calls to Tory offices had been
positive, as people welcomed Mr Major's readiness 'to face down rebels in
his own party'.
Sir Giles Shaw, a member of the executive of the influential 1922 Committee
of Tory MPs, told BBC Radio: 'After one hell of a week, the prime minister
has shown robust and pretty steely views and one must applaud him for that.'
The toughness was also apparent in the withdrawal of the Tory party whip
from Mr Rupert Allason, the MP for Torbay and the only Conservative not to
support the government in last Friday's confidence vote.
The particularly important role given to his local constituency association
in determining his future career was spelt out in the letter to Mr Allason
from Mr Richard Ryder, the government chief whip, which was published
yesterday.
It said: 'I have decided to suspend the whip from you until Nicholas Baker
(Mr Allason's regional Commons whip) and your association chairman recommend
your reinstatement after you have demonstrated clear and consistent support
for the government.'
Last night Torbay Conservative Association said after a meeting that Mr
Allason would explain his actions to its executive council in September.
There is no prospect of his rehabilitation before then.
While the political excitement over Mr Major's comments showed signs of
dying down, a fresh row was developing over related newspaper telephone
lines.
The Daily Mirror and The Sun advertised telephone numbers to enable people
to hear the tapes of conversations they had published - the Daily Mirror the
off-the-record conversation on Friday in which the prime minister spoke
bitterly of the difficulties of managing with a small majority, and The Sun
the private comments by Mr Major just before last year's election.
The lines were yesterday banned by the telephone information services
watchdog as 'an unreasonable invasion of privacy'. The companies running
them were given 24 hours to justify the services.
</TEXT>
