<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 93 / Fishermen warn they may become an endangered species: Rules
to conserve stocks are being challenged in the courts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A STIFF breeze is blowing across Newhaven harbour, East Sussex, and most of
the port's trawlers are lying idle. Strong winds in the English Channel have
put paid to another morning's fishing. It's a scene which helps to explain
why fishermen are locked in bitter conflict with the government over the
future of their industry.
This autumn the National Federation of Fishermen's Organisations will ask
the High Court, through a judicial review, to block the introduction of new
rules designed to conserve fish stocks. The rules, implementing an European
Community-wide agreement, mean that boats over 10 metres long will be
limited next year to the same number of days they spent at sea in 1991.
The federation says a typical trawler spends about 180 days at sea and warn
that this could be cut to 158 days under the new rules, reducing a crew
member's pay of up to Pounds 15,000 by as much as Pounds 3,000.
The fishermen say the unpredictability of the British weather adds to the
injustice of being forced to tie up their boats for part of the year. 'A
great deal of the UK fleet is controlled by the weather,' said Mr David
Scott, federation president and chairman of the Newhaven fishermen's
co-operative. The best fishing months in Newhaven are September to December,
but if trawler crews save their quota of days until then, only to be stymied
by the gales of the last couple of years, they would have to risk dangerous
seas or be left with unused days and less fish.
Mr Scott said: 'This question of tie-ups is the most immoral act that's ever
been put upon one nation's fishermen.'
The rules were designed to help reduce the UK's fishing capacity by 19 per
cent by the end of 1996 in order to preserve dwindling supplies of fish. EC
officials say cod is particularly hard hit, with North Sea breeding stocks
at a record low of about 90,000 tonnes against what scientists warn is a
sustainable level of 150,000 tonnes.
Fishermen say they have no quibble with the principle of conservation. But
this particular legislation has spurred them to blockade ports and organise
lobbies of parliament.
If the rules take effect, they will be forced to flout them to save their
businesses, said Mr Scott. 'No way will they ever conform to being tied up.
There will be head-on confrontation,' he added.
Their main complaint is that other EC fishermen do not face such
restrictions. 'We'll have UK vessels tied up and what they don't catch will
be caught by the other member states, so it really won't do anything for
conservation,' said Mr Scott. He was referring particularly to French and
Belgian fishermen in the Channel. But EC officials point out that Dutch
crews, the main catchers of sole and plaice in the southern North Sea, have
for some time faced limits on the days they can spend at sea.
The federation, which represents 6,000 fishermen in England, Wales, Northern
Ireland and the Channel Islands, also argues that costs such as insurance,
harbour dues and boat maintenance will still have to be paid even though
income may drop. Fishermen are already feeling squeezed by the 15 per cent
to 30 per cent fall in the price of fish at the start of the year, when
cheap imports from Russia, Iceland, Poland and Norway flooded the EC market.
In tandem with its legal fight, the federation is drawing up an alternative
conservation package to put to ministers in September. It includes larger
mesh sizes for nets, bigger landing sizes and escape panels in trawlers -
all designed to prevent juvenile fish from being caught before they can
breed.
Mrs Gillian Shephard, minister for agriculture, fisheries and food, called
for common international action this month, warning that without it, 'there
will be no fish for anyone to fish, no jobs for any fishermen and no
security for any fishermen's families'.
But conservationists are partly on the fishermen's side over the tie-up
rules. Ms Mary Munson, fisheries campaigner at Greenpeace, said policing the
seas is at the heart of the problem. UK fishermen have been incensed at the
sight of trawlers from other EC countries fishing illegally in British
waters. However rigorous the UK's 142 port inspectors are, said Ms Munson,
'it's the nature of fishing that you can't get an inspector to go on every
boat'.
She added that better monitoring of landings and inspection of boats at port
by all EC states is essential, along with measures such as the European
Commission's proposal to track boats by satellite.
UK fishermen, suspicious of their European competitors, claim two hidden
agendas: that the EC wants to reduce UK capacity to make way for the large
Spanish and Portuguese fleets, and that Britain is intent on forcing its
fishermen out of the industry without having to compensate them.
Ministry officials agree the choice of the controversial 'tie-up' system was
partly based on cost, although it is also seen as more enforceable than the
conservation measures favoured by fishermen. The main alternative to
restricting fishing days - a large-scale programme to pay fishermen to stop
fishing - would be more than the Treasury would accept in the present
financial climate.
The government has already announced a three-year Pounds 25m programme,
which it hopes will reduce the fleet by about 5 per cent. The UK has 11,000
vessels, of which 3,500 are over 10 metres. The fishermen and their
supporters in parliament want a programme worth at least Pounds 50m.
Introduction of the tie-up rules has been postponed from October to next
January to allow for wider consultation. If the federation wins its High
Court action, the government may be forced back to the drawing board. Other
member states, facing the same pressure to cut their fleets, will watch the
outcome with interest.
</TEXT>
